### Macros in Rust

Macros are a form of metaprogramming that generate code at compile time. Rust has declarative macros (`macro_rules!`) and procedural macros.

---

### Macro Types

| Type | Description |
|------|-------------|
| `macro_rules!` | Declarative macros, pattern matching |
| Procedural macros | Function-like, derive, attribute macros |
| Built-in macros | `println!`, `vec!`, `assert!`, etc. |

---

### Declarative Macros

```rust
// Simple macro
macro_rules! say_hello {
    () => {
        println!("Hello!");
    };
}

// Macro with parameters
macro_rules! create_function {
    ($func_name:ident, $val:expr) => {
        fn $func_name() {
            println!("Value: {}", $val);
        }
    };
}

create_function!(foo, 42);

// Repetition
macro_rules! vec {
    ( $( $x:expr ),* ) => {
        {
            let mut temp_vec = Vec::new();
            $(
                temp_vec.push($x);
            )*
            temp_vec
        }
    };
}
```

> **Key Point:** Macros operate on the syntax tree level and can take variable numbers of arguments. `macro_rules!` uses pattern matching to transform input code. Procedural macros (like `#[derive(Debug)]`) are more powerful but require a separate crate.

codeExample:
macro_rules! calculate {
    (add $a:expr, $b:expr) => {
        $a + $b
    };
    (sub $a:expr, $b:expr) => {
        $a - $b
    };
    (mul $a:expr, $b:expr) => {
        $a * $b
    };
}

fn main() {
    println!("Add: {}", calculate!(add 10, 5));
    println!("Sub: {}", calculate!(sub 10, 5));
    println!("Mul: {}", calculate!(mul 10, 5));
}
